JOHANNESBURG - A second case of the coronavirus has been confirmed in South Africa and the Health Department is urging all citizens to remain calm. Health Minister Dr Zweli Mkhize says his department is committed to mitigating the uncontrollable spread of the COVID-19 virus and wants cooperation from the public and the media during this period. He has cautioned against believing every piece of coronavirus information on social media. “Stop spreading fake news that either ridicule the efforts of the health workers or that frighten people...” Mkhize said. WATCH: Doctor of SA's first coronavirus patient speaks Mkhize says the public will be informed on all relevant developments and that all South Africans should be prepared and protect themselves. The Health Department says a 39-year-old woman was in direct contact with the first confirmed patient in KwaZulu-Natal. She will be admitted to Charlotte Maxeke Hospital in Gauteng for quarantine and treatment. READ: #CoronavirusInSA: How to stay safe The woman was part of a group of 10 that had travelled to Italy. The first patient and his wife were also part of the group. The Health Department is confirming a second case of coronavirus in South Africa. The 39-year-old had been in direct contact with the first case in KZN. Courtesy #DStv403 Government is also still planning to repatriate all South Africans living in Wuhan city. About 151 South Africans living in Wuhan city will be evacuated, and the health department says none of them has shown any symptoms.